(8, '35th Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA)', 'BILECO invites all member-consumer-owners to attend to its 35th Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA) meeting on August 25, Friday, via Facebook Live.\r\n \r\nNarito ang dalawang paraan upang makapag-rehistro:\r\nUna: Bileconek Mobile App\r\n1. I-download and BILECONEK MOBILE App sa Google Play Store\r\n2. Buksan ang BILECONEK MOBILE app at mag-login as guest\r\n3. I-type ang BILECO account no. sa pamamagitan ng:\r\n‚Ä¢ Pag-scan ng bar code o\r\n‚Ä¢ Manual na pag-input\r\n4. Kapag verified na, i-check kung tama ang detalye at i-click ang register\r\n5. I-type ang mobile contact number\r\n6. Pumirma sa screen at i-click ang save\r\n7. I-upload ang litrato ng valid government issued ID ng MCO (i.e. voter‚Äôs ID, senior citizen‚Äôs ID, driver‚Äôs license, atbp.) Pagkatapos ay i-click ang proceed.\r\n8. I-save sa gallery ang na-generate na stub number at QR code na siyang gagamitin sa raffle draw.\r\nPangalawa: I-type ang link na ito sa iyong browser\r\nhttps://www.bileco.net/agma-registration/', '1740105386_agma.png', '2023-08-22 00:00:00'),
(9, 'SEN. TULFO AND SANGGUNIANG BAYAN OF SAN JOSE RECOGNIZE THE EFFORT AND INTERVENTION OF NEA ADMIN ALMEDA IN RESOLVING OCC. MINDORO POWER CRISIS', 'In a public hearing of the Senate Committee on Energy yesterday, 18 May 2023, Senator Raffy Tulfo\r\ncommended NEA Administrator Antonio Mariano Almeda for putting an end to decades of unstable\r\npower supply in Occidental Mindoro.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúI commend you for that, Mr. Almeda. Ayun ‚Äòyung kasabihan na kung gusto maraming paraan, kung\r\nayaw maraming dahilan. In this case, gumawa kayo ng paraan para ma-solve itong problema,‚Äù Sen.\r\nTulfo said.\r\n\r\nLikewise, the Sangguniang Bayan of San Jose, Occidental Mindoro passed a resolution recognizing\r\nthe effort and intervention of the National Electrification Administration, thru Administrator Almeda,\r\nin resolving the power crisis in the province.\r\n\r\nApproved during its 18th Regular Session, Resolution No. 7368 declared that the Sangguniang\r\nBayan is one with the thousands of member-consumer-owners in appreciating the effort and\r\nassistance of NEA in ensuring a better and more stable power supply for the people and the whole\r\nprovince, which they sincerely believe will be the greatest factor in achieving the municipality‚Äôs goal\r\ntowards the more progressive economy.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúNow therefore, be it resolved to express heartfelt gratitude to the National Electrification\r\nAdministration (NEA), thru its Administrator Antonio Mariano C. Almeda, for their effort and\r\nintervention in the power crisis being experienced by the people of Occidental Mindoro,‚Äù the\r\nresolution reads.\r\n\r\nAs the lead agency in resolving the power crisis in the province, the Administrator traveled a couple\r\nof times to Occidental Mindoro. Last April, the NEA Chief led the switch-on ceremony of the three\r\npower plants of Occidental Mindoro Consolidated Power Corporation (OMCPC) after its owner Mr.\r\nLuis Manuel Banzon agreed to simultaneously operate the power plants to avert the 20-hour\r\nrotational brownout in the province.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúSince April 28, the whole province is not experiencing any more brownouts‚Ä¶ We, in the energy\r\nsector, meaning DOE, NEA and ERC, are in constant communication for the long-term solutions for\r\nOccidental Mindoro,‚Äù the Administrator said during the Senate hearing.###', '1740106707_media-release-01-01-2048x760.png', '2023-05-22 00:00:00'),
(10, 'BILECO joins the BILCOMNET Serbisyo Caravan', 'BILECO joined in the recently concluded serbisyo caravan held in Brgy. Tabunan, Almeria today, April 19, 2023.\r\nAmong the services provided by the coop includes, new connection application of electric connection, updating/renaming of accounts, and senior citizen discount application.\r\n\r\nThe event was facilitated by Biliran Communicators Network (BILCOMNET) participated by local and national government agencies who also provided their services to the public.', '1740106968_IMG_0336-2048x1365.jpg', '2023-04-19 00:00:00'),
(11, 'LOOK: BILECO linemen undergo knot tying training', 'Selected line workers of BILECO underwent a training for knot tying today, April 3, 2023, at the coop‚Äôs Solidarity Hall.\r\n\r\nThe said training was conducted by the Boy Scout of the Philippines (BSP) Biliran Council training team, namely: Mr. Diosdado C. Paa, Mr. Crisanto B. Rosario and Mr. Josefel S. Padoga. Mr. Paa and Mr. Rosario, both school heads from Caibiran National High School and Bool Elementary School, respectively, discussed the techniques in basic knot tying, while Mr. Padoga, Teacher I of Cabucgayan Central School, talked about the advance techniques in knot tying.\r\n\r\nThe training aims to equip the participants in the basic knot tying which is useful in their day-to-day activities as linemen. It is also part of their preparations for the upcoming Linemen‚Äôs Rodeo, one of the competitions in the FRECORlympics 2023 participated by 11 electric cooperatives in Region 8 to be held this month.##', '1740109296_DSC_8136-2048x1365.jpg', '2023-04-03 00:00:00'),
(12, 'LOOK: BILECO women employees participate in the 26th Provincial Women‚Äôs Congress', 'Around 15 female personnel and officers of the coop joined the celebration held on Tuesday, 21 March 2023 at the BiPSU Gym. The event commenced with a holy mass followed by a parade from the Naval Cathedral to the venue. The coop ladies together with women participants from the eight (8) municipalities of Biliran Province attended the lectures on mental health and Republic Act 9262 or the Anti-Violence Against Women and their Children Act which were discussed by resource speakers: Ms. Vanessa V. Ramirez and Ms. Corazon A. David, respectively. The latter also discussed the anti-cybercrime law and right parenting.\r\n \r\nThe program was hosted by the Provincial Council for Women‚Äôs Welfare, Inc. (PCWWI) headed by its president, Dr. Cecil M. Espina, and was also attended by Governor Gerard Roger M. Espina together with the municipal mayors, namely: Mayor Gretchen Stephanie M. Espina (Naval), Mayor Rhodessa D. Revita (Caibiran) and Mayor Humphrey Olimba (Culaba).', '1740123621_IMG_0015-2048x1365.jpg', '2023-03-22 00:00:00'),
(13, 'IN PHOTOS: BILCOMNET holds its first quarter meeting at BILECO', 'Biliran Communicators Network (BILCOMNET) is composed of information officers coming from LGUs, local and national agencies in Biliran Province. Its first quarter meeting was held today, 15 March 2023, at the Solidarity Hall of BILECO.\r\n\r\nBILECO ISD Manager Allan Joseph Borrinaga delivered a welcome message to the group, while Philippine Information Agency (PIA) Biliran Manager Rodrigo Victoria led the discussions and stated the 2023 plans of BILCOMNET.', '1740123756_DSC_7005-2048x1367.jpg', '2023-03-15 00:00:00'),
(17, 'BILECO accommodates additional 30 OJTs, work immersion students from BiPSU', 'The Coop accommodated 30 more on-the-job trainees (OJTs) or student interns and work immersion students from BiPSU bringing a total of 53 OJTs and immersion students in the Coop for this year. The trainees include four (4) student interns of Bachelor of Arts in Economics (BA Econ), Ten (10) student interns of Bachelor of Science in Business Administration (BSBA) and six (6) student interns coming from Bachelor of Science in Information System (BSIS) program. BA Econ student interns are required to complete 350 hours, BSIS need 486 hours, while BSBA student interns must complete 600 hours of training in the Coop according to their respective endorsement letters.\r\n\r\nAlso, a total of Ten (10) students from BiPSU Laboratory High School were already deployed last week nearing to complete their 10 days work immersion.\r\n\r\nAll of them were assigned to the different departments/sections of the Coop to assist in the day-to-day operations of BILECO.', '1740365036_DSC_6891-2048x1367.jpg', '2023-03-14 00:00:00'),
(18, '2023 Nationwide Simultaneous Earthquake Drill (NSED)', 'IN PHOTOS: BILECO office personnel participates in the 2023 Nationwide Simultaneous Earthquake Drill (NSED)\r\n\r\nSeveral coop employees ducked down to the floor, took cover under their desks, held on until the shaking stopped and safely went outside the building towards an open area during the earthquake drill conducted at its office premises today, March 9.\r\n\r\nThe NSED is being conducted quarterly nationwide and is spearheaded by the NDRRMC together with the Office of the Civil Defense. This is done to intensify earthquake preparedness and to instill in the mind of every person the practice of duck, cover and hold when ground shaking occurs or during earthquakes.', '1740365128_DSC_6690-2048x1367.jpg', '2023-03-09 00:00:00'),
(19, 'BILECO Notice of District Elections in Cabucgayan, Caibiran, and Culaba for June', 'Please be informed that BILECO will be conducting its regular district elections of the Board of Directors for the three (3) districts on the following schedule:\r\n\r\nDISTRICTS	DEADLINE FOR FILING OF COC	ELECTION DAY\r\nCabucgayan (District 5)	June 5	June 15\r\nCaibiran (District 6)	June 12	June 22\r\nCulaba (District 7)	June 19	June 29\r\nEach district is entitled to one seat on the BILECO Board of Directors with the following term of office:\r\n\r\nDISTRICTS	TERM OF OFFICE\r\nCabucgayan	2024-2027\r\nCaibiran	2024-2027\r\nCulaba	2024-2027\r\nAny member whose name has been inadvertently excluded from the master list of Member-Consumers but failed to avail of the remedies during the inclusion/exclusion period shall not be allowed to vote. Such failure to avail of the remedies during the Inclusion/exclusion period shall be considered a waiver of the member‚Äôs right to vote.\r\n\r\nDeadline for the inclusion/exclusion period shall be as follows:\r\n\r\nDISTRICT	DEADLINE\r\nCabucgayan	June 5\r\nCaibiran	June 12\r\nCulaba	June 19\r\nInterested and qualified MCOs desiring to run for Directorship may secure the needed forms from the Institutional Services Department (ISD) of BILECO, Caraycaray, Naval, Biliran.\r\n\r\nThe QUALIFICATIONS and DISQUALIFICATIONS of candidates are as follows:\r\n\r\nQUALIFICATIONS\r\n\r\nAny member who is entitled to vote and has the following qualifications can be elected or continue as member of the Board of Directors:\r\n\r\nHe or she is a Filipino citizen;\r\nHe or she is a graduate of a four (4)-year course;\r\nHe or she should at least be twenty-one (21) years old and not over seventy (70) years old, on the date of election;\r\nHe or she is of good moral character which may be established with the submission of a certificate with all of the following:\r\nBarangay where the candidate resides;\r\nNational Bureau of Investigation;\r\nPhilippine National Police; or\r\nLeader of the religious sect where the candidate is affiliated\r\nHe or she is a member of the EC in good standing for the last five (5) years immediately preceding the election or appointment and shall continue to be a member in good standing during his or her incumbency. A member of good standing shall mean that said member:\r\n5.1 Must have no unsettled or outstanding obligations to the cooperative during his/her membership in the cooperative whether personal or through commercial or industrial connections of which he or she is the owner or co-owner.\r\n\r\n5.2 An unsettled or outstanding obligations is an account which has not been paid within seven (7) days after the due date. ‚ÄúDue date‚Äù shall refer to the date of receipt of the obligation. Provided, that in the case of power bills, it shall refer to the ninth (9th) day reckoned from receipt thereof. For incumbent members of the EC Board who will seek re-election, unsettled or outstanding obligation shall be deemed to include power bills, cash advances, disallowances (including NEA audit findings) and materials and equipment issuances. At any given time during his membership in the cooperative, he or she must be totally free of any unsettled or outstanding obligations and/or disallowances with the EC.\r\n\r\nHas not been apprehended for electric pilferage. A mere apprehension of electric pilferage by the EC, even without conviction for such offense by any court, shall be a valid ground for disqualification. The word ‚Äúapprehension‚Äù should be taken in the strict context as used in Republic Act No. 7832, otherwise known as ‚ÄúAnti-Electricity and Electric Transmission Lines or Materials Pilferage Act of 1994‚Äù, which means that a person is caught in flagrante delicto for violating the provision of the said Act.\r\nHas not been removed for cause as director or an employee from any EC. In general, removal or termination of service from the EC is caused by a grave offense or violation/s of policies, rules and regulations. A former director or employee with a record of termination/removal for cause from public office or for just cause as defined in Article 282 of the Labor Code as amended, shall not be qualified to be elected or appointed as director of an EC.\r\nHe or she is an actual resident and consumer in the district that he or she seeks to represent for at least two (2) years immediately preceding the election; and\r\nHe or she has attended at least two (2) Annual General Membership Assemblies (AGMA) for the last five (5) years immediately preceding the election or appointment.\r\nFor a qualified government employee, he/she must present a written Certification from his/her Department Secretary/Regional Director/Local Chief Executive or his duly authorized representative allowing him/her to run and sit as director at the time of his/her filing of Certificate of Candidacy;\r\nAdditional qualification as per AGMA RESOLUTION No. 2018-01 states that he or she must have participated/voted at least once for the last five (5) years immediately preceding the election.\r\nDISQUALIFICATIONS\r\n\r\nFurther, any person shall be ineligible to be elected or appointed as member of the Board of Directors of an EC if:\r\n\r\nSuch person or his or her spouse holds any public office. For the purpose of disqualification, a person holding an elective position or an appointive position with a salary grade of sixteen (SG-16) or higher or its equivalent shall not be eligible to be elected as member of the Board of Directors or Officers of an EC.\r\nSuch person or his or her spouse has been a candidate in the immediately preceding local or national elections.\r\nSuch person has been convicted by final judgment of a crime involving moral turpitude.\r\nSuch person has been terminated from public office/government employment or private employment for just cause as defined in Article 282 of the Labor Code. For this purpose, termination from public office shall mean removal.\r\nSuch person is related within the fourth civil degree of consanguinity or affinity to any member of the EC Board of Directors, General Manager, Department Manager, NEA-appointed Project Supervisor (PS) or Acting General Manager (AGM) and its equivalent or higher positions.\r\nSuch person is employed by or has financial interest in a competing enterprise or a business selling electric energy or electrical hardware to the cooperative or doing business with the EC including, but not limited to, the use or rental of poles. For this purpose of this By-Laws, ‚Äúdoing business‚Äù shall refer to the transactions related to the core or main line of business of the EC, which is conveyance of electricity through its distribution facilities.\r\nIncumbent GM and employees of electric cooperatives are not allowed to run as member of the board of another cooperative.\r\nThe disqualification of one of the spouses shall mean the disqualification of the other.', '1740367125_bilecologo.png', '2024-05-16 00:00:00'),
(20, '‚ÄòPhilippine Electricity Market Corporation (PEMC) Notice of Public Hearing‚Äô', 'Notice of Public Hearing\r\n\r\nMon, 20 Feb 2023\r\n\r\nNotice is hereby given that on 10 January 2023, the Philippine Electricity Market Corporation (PEMC) and the Independent Electricity Market Operator of the Philippines, Inc. (IEMOP) filed the Joint Application dated 26 October 2022 in the case titled, ‚ÄúIn the Matter of the Application for the Issuance of Rules on the Price Determination Methodology for the Implementation of the Co-Optimized Energy and Reserve Market in the Wholesale Electricity Spot Market (WESM)‚Äù docketed as ERC Case No. 2023-002 RC.\r\n\r\nThe Joint Application was filed with the ERC seeking the latter‚Äôs approval of the amendments to the Price Determination Methodology for the Wholesale Electricity Spot Market (WESM) to include relevant methodologies and procedures for the trading of reserves or ancillary services in the WESM.\r\n\r\nIn the Order and Notice of Public Hearing, both dated 10 February 2023, the ERC scheduled the Joint Application for hearing on the following dates:\r\n\r\nDate and Time\r\n\r\nVenue\r\n\r\nPurpose\r\n\r\n07 March 2023\r\n\r\n(Tuesday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nERC Hearing Room, 11th Floor, Exquadra Tower, 1 Jade Drive, Ortigas Center, Brgy. San Antonio, Pasig City\r\n\r\nDetermination of compliance with jurisdictional requirements, and Expository Presentation for Luzon Stakeholders\r\n\r\n16 March 2023\r\n\r\n(Thursday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nERC Visayas Area Operations Division (VAOD), 7th Floor, Kepwealth Building, Samar Loop, Cebu Business Park\r\n\r\nExpository Presentation for Visayas Stakeholders\r\n\r\n23 March 2023\r\n\r\n(Thursday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nERC Mindanao Area Operations Division (MAOD), 6th Floor, BIZ Bldg., c/o BORMAHECO, INC., 209 J.P. Laurel Avenue, Bajada, Davao City\r\n\r\nExpository Presentation for Mindanao Stakeholders\r\n\r\n11 April 2023\r\n\r\n(Tuesday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nERC Hearing Room, 11th Floor, Exquadra Tower, 1 Jade Drive, Ortigas Center, Brgy. San Antonio, Pasig City\r\n\r\nPre-Trial Conference and Presentation of Evidence\r\n\r\n18 Apil 2023\r\n\r\n(Tuesday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nPresentation of Evidence\r\n\r\n25 April 2023\r\n\r\n(Tuesday)\r\n\r\nTwo o‚Äôclock in the afternoon (2:00 P.M.)\r\n\r\nPresentation of Evidence\r\n\r\nAs stated in the Notice of Public Hearing, any interested stakeholder may submit its comments and/or clarifications at least one (1) calendar day prior to the scheduled initial hearing via electronic mail at docket@erc.ph, copy furnish the Legal Service through legal@erc.ph.  Moreover, any person who has an interest in the subject matter may become a party by filing with the ERC via electronic mail at docket@erc.ph, copy furnish the Legal Service through legal@erc.ph a verified Petition to Intervene at least five (5) calendar days prior to the date of the initial hearing and subject to the requirements under Rule 9 of the ERC Revised Rules of Practice and Procedure.  Likewise, all other persons who may want their views known to the ERC with respect to the subject matter of the case may file via electronic mail at docket@erc.ph, copy furnish the Legal Service through legal@erc.ph, their Opposition or Comment at least five (5) calendar days prior to the date of the initial hearing and subject to the requirements under Rule 9 of the ERC Revised Rules of Practice and Procedure.\r\n\r\nA copy of the Joint Application may be accessed through this link or at the ERC official website at www.erc.gov.ph. You may also email your request for a full copy of the same from the PEMC Legal Department at legal@wesm.ph.\r\n\r\nFor further information, please refer to the ERC Order and Notice of Public Hearing both dated 10 February 2023.', '1740368335_images.png', '2023-03-08 00:00:00'),
(21, '‚ÄòDugong Lineman, para sa Bayan‚Äô', 'BILECO conducted bloodletting activity today, 17 February 2023, held at the Coop‚Äôs Solidarity Hall in coordination with Biliran Provincial Hospital (BPH).\r\nAmong the qualified donors include 27 BILECO employees, six on-the-job trainees (OJTs) from BIPSU, one BLAZE member and two family members of coop employees. A total of 36 bags of blood were successfully extracted and were brought to the BPH.\r\nThis undertaking activity is aligned in this year‚Äôs 50th anniversary celebration of BILECO and part of the Coop‚Äôs corporate social responsibility program to help save lives.', '1740374439_DSC_5931-2048x1364.jpg', '2023-02-17 00:00:00'),
(22, 'Love is in BILECO', 'BILECO held a program for all its employees to celebrate this year‚Äôs romantic celebration of Valentine‚Äôs Day.\r\nThe event kicked off with a Holy Mass followed by a series of games with prizes, photo op for MCOs, film showing and a raffle where all employees had the chance to win a dinner date for two. Five lucky employees can bring their spouse, lover or family member and will enjoy a splendid meal at a local diner.\r\nGM Gerardo N. Oledan delivered the welcome message and encouraged everyone to spend quality time with their loved ones.\r\n‚ÄúLove is Patient. Love is Kind. üòä‚Äù', '1740377996_DSC_5524-2048x1367.jpg', '2023-02-14 00:00:00'),
(23, 'BILECO visits BGI', 'BILECO Board of Directors together with General Manager Gerardo N. Oledan visited the ongoing construction of Biliran Geothermal Inc. (BGI) pad site yesterday, 8 February 2023.\r\nThe team was welcomed by the Site Manager of BGI Mr. Thaddeus Barrameda. A brief orientation was done for safety rules which includes the wearing of personal protective equipment prior to the site visit. While, BGI Project Development Manager Mr. Romulo Tilos toured the team on site.\r\nThe visit of BILECO is in connection to the proposed embedded connection of BGI to the cooperative. The construction is expected to end by the first quarter of 2023 as mentioned in their previous meetings.', '1740378705_DSC_4858-2048x1367.jpg', '2023-02-08 00:00:00'),
(24, 'NEA VOWS TO ACHIEVE TOTAL ELECTRIFICATION BY 2028', 'Date : January 31, 2023\r\nSubject : Media Release\r\nTitle : NEA VOWS TO ACHIEVE TOTAL ELECTRIFICATION BY 2028\r\nThe National Electrification Administration (NEA) announced its plans and programs that will drive\r\nthe country toward achieving sustainable and inclusive economic growth.\r\nAt the recently concluded NEA Strategic Thinking Conference-Workshop in Pampanga, NEA\r\nAdministrator Antonio Mariano Almeda vowed to attain 100-percent electrification in the country by\r\n2028.\r\n‚ÄúChallenge accepted. By 2028, 100 percent electrification. Double time tayo. My administration will\r\nalways be anchored in the principle of good governance. I will make sure that the Sitio Electrification\r\nProgram funds are utilized well,‚Äù the NEA Chief declared on the first day of the conference last 26\r\nJanuary 2023.\r\nEnergy Assistant Secretary and NEA Board of Administrators (BOA) Alternate Chairman Mario\r\nMarasigan graced the event and assured NEA and the electric cooperatives (ECs) of DOE‚Äôs further\r\nguidance in achieving total electrification.\r\n‚ÄúWe hope that the NEA will take the lead, very actively in guiding our electric cooperatives to\r\ncomplete their local total electrification program because this is how we will break our targets in\r\nelectrification. Definitely, the Department of Energy will provide guidance,‚Äù Asec. Marasigan said.\r\nMoreover, the NEA will help in the facilitation of the Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic\r\nAct No. 11646 or the Microgrid Systems Act, which aims to accelerate total electrification and ensure\r\nthe provision of quality, reliable, and secure electricity service in unserved and underserved areas.\r\nThe agency will also be playing a very strategic role in addressing the power rate hikes. The\r\nAdministrator will be firm in boosting embedded renewable energy supply among the electric\r\ncooperatives.\r\nTo cope with the ever-changing conditions of the industry, Administrator Almeda is prioritizing as\r\nwell the restructuring of the agency. He will likewise intensify the capacity building of NEA and EC\r\nemployees.\r\nThe three-day conference-workshop was also attended by the rural electrification partners of NEA\r\nsuch as the Philippine Rural Electric Cooperatives Association (PHILRECA), National Association\r\nof General Managers of Electric Cooperatives (NAGMEC), Central Luzon Electric Cooperatives\r\nAssociation (CLECA), Federation of Rural Electric Cooperatives in Region VIII (FRECOR 8), Central\r\nVisayas Electric Cooperatives Association (CEVECA) and Association of Mindanao Rural Electric\r\nCooperatives (AMRECO). They have expressed their full support and cooperation to the agency.###', '1740379622_media-release-01-01-2048x760.png', '2023-02-02 00:00:00'),
(25, '2022 IN REVIEW', '2022 IN REVIEW\r\n \r\nMCO EMPOWERMENT\r\n\r\nMCO empowerment program continues to takeoff since its inception in 2019 thru the following programs and activities:\r\n\r\nBILECO conducted MCO re-organization in each barangay thru Barangayan where new sets of officers were elected and crucial topics discussed.\r\nMCOs actively took part in the EC-wideregular district election for the position of Board of Directors of BILECO. New BOD representatives were elected in the districts of Almeria, Caibiran, Culaba and Naval, while incumbents in other districts retain. Biliran district, with opposing candidates, recorded the highest turn-out of votes at 35%.\r\nAbout 5,600 MCOs, or 14% of the billed customers, have attended the Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA) held thru face to face and virtual platform via Facebook Live.\r\nBILECO held meetings and dialogues with its allied organizations, such as the B-EMPOWER, MSEAC, BAPA, and the accredited barangay electricians. They are BILECO‚Äôs strong allies in channeling information down to the MCOs, and active partner in achieving the corporate goals and objectives.\r\nALIPDWA, a local association in Almeria, was the first recipient of BILECO‚Äôs livelihood program. The aim of this program is to help in the economic alleviation and improvement of the quality of life of indigent MCOs.\r\nBILECO tapped with TESDA-CNSAT to provide free five-day training on Electrical Installation of CCTV and Fire Detection and Alarm System for its barangay electricians. It has also shouldered the assessment fee of around 40 electricians.\r\n \r\nCAPACITATING THE WORKFORCE\r\n\r\nIn line with Mental Health Awareness Month celebration, BILECO conducted a Psychological First Aid (PFA) Training to all employees to equip them with practical knowledge how to deal and assist in a healthy recovery of persons who experienced traumatic events, disasters or severe crisis.\r\n\r\nAlso, BILECO spearheaded a Refresher Course on Good Customer Service, recognizing the importance of customers in the viability and growth of ECs. It reminded the employees how to deal with customers with courtesy, honesty, respect and enthusiasm.\r\n\r\nLikewise, to ensure safety in the workplace and employees, BILECO initiated a random drug testing to its employees, which rendered a zero-positive result.\r\n\r\nOther trainings and seminars organized by local, regional and national agencies or associations such as NEA, PHILRECA, DOE and ERC were likewise attended for personal and professional advancement.\r\n\r\nELECTRIFICATION PROGRAM \r\n\r\nBILECO continued to fulfill its mandate by lighting the remaining unenergized communities in the province. Four sitios were energized under the Sitio Electrification Program (SEP), namely: Sitio Puntod, Sitio Lawaan, Sitio Ligating and Sitio Haropohop benefitting more than 60 households. BILECO also funded the electrification project to Sitio Bagongbong in Caucab, Almeria with over 20 beneficiaries.\r\n\r\nTwo (2) housing projects of the National Housing Authority were energized this year: the Villa El Blanco in Brgy. Jamorawon, Almeria and the Cool Mont Crest in Brgy. Villa Caneja, Naval, with nearly 800 units lighted.\r\n\r\nTo accelerate electrification, BILECO initiated the Pailaw Program also dubbed ‚ÄòLight Now, Pay Later‚Äô fashioned for indigent households. Around 1,000 households have availed of the program to date.\r\n\r\nSYSTEM IMPROVEMENT\r\n\r\nBILECO has energized the 3.15 MVA transformer in Brgy. San Roque, Biliran, in anticipation to the rising demand of power next year. BILECO has forecasted economic boom with the cessation of COVID-19 pandemic. Commercial establishments are signifying intent to expand their businesses in the province, and government infrastructures are on the rise.\r\n\r\nOther improvements implemented include the reconductoring from Brgy. Baso to Salawad, Cabucgayan, installation of 3 units AVR for power quality improvement, replacement of bare with insulated wires in highly vegetated areas, upgrading of secondary to primary lines and automation of circuit reclosers for easy monitoring and controlling.\r\n\r\nWARRIORS OF LIGHT\r\n\r\nBILECO, together with 120 ECs nationwide, have celebrated the National Linemen Appreciation Day in recognition to the courage, contribution and sacrifices of all warriors of light. Mr. Juanito Garcia, Jr. of BILECO was one of Region 8‚Äôs awardees of the 2022 Gawad Parangal Para sa Natatanging Linemen conferred by the Philippine Rural Electric Cooperatives Association, Inc. (PHILRECA).\r\n\r\nBILECO warriors were also among the dynamic participants to the task force kapatid in LEYECO IV and SOLECO after Typhoon Odette ravaged the area. The task force helped in the power restoration and rehabilitation activities.\r\n\r\nOUTREACH ACTIVITIES\r\n\r\nIn consonance with DENR-EMB R8 MOA, BILECO successfully conducted clean-up drive at Sambulawan Creek in Brgy. Caraycaray, Naval.\r\n\r\nIn participation with the 2022 National Electrification Administration-Electric Cooperatives (NEA-ECs) simultaneous tree planting and line clearing, BILECO planted 300 assorted seedlings in coordination with the Provincial Environment and Natural Resources Office (PENRO) Biliran at Sitio Magtaran-an, Brgy. Talustusan, Naval on August 26.\r\n\r\nBILECO and DSWD spearheaded the provision of cash assistance to selected indigent MCOs thru Pantawid Liwang Program (PLP) 5 funded by the Association of Philippine Electric Cooperatives (APEC) Party-list. Over 800 MCOs in the province have benefitted from the said program since it started in 2020.\r\n\r\nThe year ended with sharing and thanksgiving in Sitio Cabungasan thru BILECO‚Äôs first ever Pasko Fiesta sa Nayon. Over 40 households received grocery packs and used clothes. They also enjoyed the modest meal, parlor games and surprises prepared for them.\r\n\r\nIEC INITIATIVES\r\n\r\nWhen power rates skyrocketed, BILECO faced attacks from MCOs. In response, the Coop conducted massive information drive to minimize and counter the bashing.\r\n\r\nBILECO attended the Sangguniang Panlalawigan hearing and Sangguniang Bayan (SB) sessions to explain the cause and action plans taken. Also, BILECO requested attendance to barangay assemblies to relay the message down to household level. Likewise, the management conducted Energy summit for its allied organizations called for the same purpose. Other IEC materials, such as leaflets, AVPs, social media posts and press releases, all help accomplish the goal.\r\n\r\nAWARDS AND RECOGNITION\r\n\r\nDespite countless hurdles, BILECO capped the year with an overwhelming triumph evidenced by several awards obtained for its 2021 operational performance.\r\n\r\nBILECO bagged seven (7) accolades during the Golden Dagitab Awards of the National Electrification Administration, which include Outstanding EC and one of the Best Regions of the Year.\r\n\r\nLikewise, PHILRECA conferred 13 awards to BILECO for exemplifying remarkable service in various areas and maintaining its Triple A (AAA) categorization.\r\n\r\nBILECO will continue to strive for excellence and keep its mantra, ‚ÄúWe serve because we care,‚Äù aflame.', '1740442364_cover.png', '2022-12-29 00:00:00'),
(26, 'NEA POWER 101 SEMINAR GOES TO VISAYAS', 'Date : December 12, 2022\r\nSubject : Media Release\r\nTitle : NEA POWER 101 SEMINAR GOES TO VISAYAS\r\n\r\nThe National Electrification Administration (NEA) gathered key officials of Electric Cooperatives\r\n(ECs) from Region VI, VII and VIII in a seminar that aims to capacitate their newly elected Board of\r\nDirectors, and newly appointed General Managers and Officer-in-Charge in understanding the\r\nElectric Power Industry.\r\n\r\nFormer Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) Commissioner Atty. Josefina Patricia M. Asirit served\r\nas the speaker at the Power 101 Seminar Series. The discussion focused on the basic concepts of\r\nthe Philippine Energy Sector, the electric power system, and the historical perspective of the Electric\r\nPower Industry.\r\n\r\nNEA Administrator Antonio Mariano C. Almeda graced the event together with Deputy Administrator\r\nfor Legal Services Atty. Rossan S.J. Rosero-Lee, Deputy Administrator for Technical Services Atty.\r\nOmar M. Mayo, Deputy Administrator for EC Management Services Engr. Ernesto Silvano, Jr. and\r\nActing Deputy Administrator for Corporate Resources and Financial Services Leila B. Bonifacio.\r\n\r\nDuring the event, the NEA Chief instructed the ECs who have not yet elected their regular Board of\r\nDirectors to immediately organize their Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA) and\r\nschedule their selection and election process as soon as possible.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúThere will be no other better personnel to manage electric cooperatives but the consumer\r\nthemselves. So, I want consumer empowerment in the electric coop industry, through the Board of\r\nDirectors, through the selection, the appointment of their own GMs,‚Äù Administrator Almeda said as\r\nhe assured the ECs of NEA‚Äôs continuing support in the initiative to bring power to the remotest place\r\nin the country.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúIyan ang marching order sa akin ng Presidente, kailangang pailawan ang kasuluk-sulukan ng\r\nPilipinas. We will work together, introducing programs that fully tap the potential of the rural\r\nelectrification program, to enhance people‚Äôs productivity and make them active partners in building\r\nsustainable rural communities. Kakampi n‚Äôyo po ako. Kakampi n‚Äôyo ang buong NEA,‚Äù the\r\nAdministrator added.\r\n\r\nA total of 88 officials from 25 ECs in the Visayas attended the seminar held in Cebu City on 06-07\r\nDecember 2022. This Power 101 Seminar is the second of its series. Last 25-26 October the Luzon\r\nECs participated in the same seminar while the Mindanao ECs are scheduled early next year.\r\n\r\nAside from Power 101 Seminar, the Administrator also attended the Christmas Party of Region VII\r\nElectric Cooperatives Association, Inc. or CEVECA. He commended the member ECs of the\r\nassociation for their exemplary performance in the electric power industry.\r\n\r\nOn behalf of Region VII ECs, CEVECA President Virgilio C. Fortich, Jr. thanked the Administrator\r\nand pledged as well their support and cooperation to NEA under the leadership of Administrator\r\nAlmeda.###', '1740380249_media-release-01-01-2048x760 (1).png', '2022-12-22 00:00:00'),
(27, 'First Pasko Sa Nayon held in Almeria', 'As a way of giving back to its MCOs, BILECO conducted its annual handog pamasko or giftgiving but with a twist. The first ever ‚ÄúPasko sa Nayon‚Äù was conducted last Friday, December 9, 2022, at Sitio Cabungasan, Brgy. Caucab, Almeria with over 40 household beneficiaries.\r\nThe activity was headed by the coop board of directors and personnel who handed grocery packs and used clothing to 46 families residing in the sitio.\r\nMoreover, adults and children alike enjoyed the parlor games with cash prizes prepared by coop personnel. The families, on the other hand, prepared meals to complement the foods prepared by the coop, to which everyone joyfully shared together.\r\nHandog pamasko is the yearly concluding activity of BILECO to thank and give importance to its MCOs within its franchise area.\r\n#BILECOHandogPamasko2022', '1740380483_DSC_1229-2048x1365.jpg', '2022-12-12 00:00:00'),
(28, 'BILECO energizes 3.15 MVA substation, supplies electricity to Biliran town', 'GM Gerardo Oledan, together with the BILECO Board of Directors, spearheaded today‚Äôs Blessing, Inauguration, and Energization of the 3.15 MVA transformer substation at Brgy. San Roque, Biliran, Biliran. Present also at the event were SB Biliran Member, Hon. Willy Corpin accompanied by SB Secretary Renan Enage, Ms. Arabella Palatan and company of Asiaphil Inc., BILECO management team and employees, and Rev. Fr. Cornelio Amante, Jr. who administered the blessing of the substation.\r\nThe said energization is in preparation for the anticipated increase in the demand of electricity within the franchise area. The coop is expecting for a higher electricity demand in 2023 and the succeeding years as more commercial establishments are signifying their intent to expand their businesses in the province, and government infrastructures are on the rise such as the construction of the new Biliran Provincial Hospital in Brgy. Larrazabal, Naval among others.\r\nDuring his message, GM Oledan announced the good news on the ongoing construction activities of the Biliran Geothermal, Inc. (BGI) for the generation of an expected 2.5 megawatts of electricity from their wells located at Sitio Pulang Yuta, Brgy. Cabibihan, Caibiran. The construction is expected to end by the first quarter of 2023 with its possible commissioning and energization come second quarter of the same year after completion of regulatory compliances from concerned agencies such as the Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) and the Department of Energy (DOE). ##\r\nRead more articles', '1740380623_DSC_9862-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-11-26 00:00:00'),
(29, 'LOOK: BILECO accepts 24 BSIT OJTs from BiPSU', 'Bachelor of Science in Industrial Technology (BSIT) major in Electrical Technology and Automotive students from Biliran Province State University (BiPSU) attended earlier today the orientation for company rules and regulation, and safety protocols before being deployed for their on-the-job training in the cooperative.\r\nThey will be assigned to the Technical Services Department to do fieldwork and other technical jobs.', '1740380742_DSC_9373-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-11-23 00:00:00'),
(30, 'BILECO holds 4th MSEAC quarterly meeting', 'BILECO held its 4th Multi-Sectoral Electrification Advisory Council (MSEAC) Quarterly Meeting at the Solidarity Hall, 2nd floor main office building of BILECO on 23 November 2022. It was attended by 44 (new and existing) MSEAC members coming from various sectors in the seven districts of the coop‚Äôs coverage area.\r\nThe MSEAC has always been one of BILECO‚Äôs strong allies in information dissemination and in achieving coop goals and objectives. During the meeting, they were reminded of their roles, duties, and responsibilities as members, and they were informed of the coop‚Äôs future plans to address power reliability in the province. Also, they were re-oriented of membership and consumer-related concerns including the reading, billing, and payment processes.\r\nNew sets of district officers and federation officers were also elected during the meeting followed by the oath-taking of the newly-elected officers.##', '1740380846_DSC_9418-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-11-23 00:00:00'),
(31, 'BILECO conducts another electricians‚Äô accreditation for 2022', 'BILECO once again conducted an accreditation for electricians practicing within its franchise area today 22 November 2022 at the coop‚Äôs Solidarity Hall of the main office building in Brgy. Caraycaray, Naval, the second time around this year after the first one was done last June 10th.\r\nThe purpose of the activity is to accredit new barangay electricians in the province and to re-accredit the practicing ones. This is mandatory for them to ensure a safe and effective process in performing house wiring installations and in compliance to the standards set forth in the Philippine Electrical Code.\r\nThe accreditation was composed of discussions about electrical safety, electricians‚Äô policy, and tariff. Also, they were shown how to properly perform meter and service dropping installations. After the discussions and tutorials, written and practical examinations were given to them.\r\nThose who will pass the accreditation will automatically become a member of BILECO League of Accredited & Skilled Electricians or BLAZE.##', '1740381095_DSC_9343-2048x1365.jpg', '2022-11-22 00:00:00'),
(32, 'NEA WELCOMES ITS NEW ADMINISTRATOR', 'Date : November 22, 2022\r\nSubject : Media Release\r\nTitle : NEA WELCOMES ITS NEW ADMINISTRATOR\r\n\r\nThe National Electrification Administration (NEA) congratulates Mr. Antonio Mariano ‚ÄúNani‚Äù C.\r\nAlmeda for being appointed by His Excellency Pres. Ferdinand Marcos, Jr. as the new NEA\r\nAdministrator.\r\n\r\nAdministrator Almeda was formally welcomed by NEA employees in an assembly held at the\r\nagency‚Äôs headquarters on Tuesday, 22 November 2022.\r\n\r\nIn his speech, the NEA Chief said he is greatly honored for the trust and confidence given by the\r\nPresident to him. He asked the NEA employees to help him fulfill the mandate of the agency.\r\n‚ÄúAko po ay isang team player, alam ko po ang halaga ng inyong participation sa aking\r\nadministrasyon. Sana po, I hope we can forge a holy alliance with honesty, integrity, dedication and\r\ndetermination,‚Äù the Administrator said.\r\n\r\nLikewise, he is looking forward for a harmonious relationship with the electric cooperatives, the\r\nagency‚Äôs implementing arm in pursuing total electrification and sustainable rural development in the\r\ncountry.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúElectric cooperatives are and should be, the wife and children of NEA, so I will try my best to forge\r\na very convenient, harmonious relationship with the electric cooperatives, so please help me. Their\r\ncooperation will matter much in the performance of our functions. Sana po samahan n‚Äôyo ako sa\r\naking trabaho. Sama-sama po tayong pailawan ang buong Pilipinas,‚Äù he added.\r\n\r\nBefore the NEA assembly, the Administrator visited the agency last 18 November 2022. He was\r\nwelcomed by former Administrator Emmanuel P. Juaneza and had a brief meeting with him together\r\nwith other NEA officials.\r\n\r\nAdministrator Almeda took his oath of office before Department of Energy (DOE) Secretary Raphael\r\nP.M. Lotilla on 17 November 2022. The ceremony was witnessed by his wife and two sons.\r\nFrom 2007-2010, Administrator Almeda served as the Deputy Executive Director of the Joint\r\nCongressional Energy Commission (JCEC), formerly known as the Joint Congressional Power\r\nCommission (JCPC), the country‚Äôs primary watchdog in the power sector. He was appointed by then\r\nRep. Juan Miguel ‚ÄúMikey‚Äù Arroyo in his capacity as the Chairman of the House Committee on Energy\r\nand Vice Chairman of JCEC.\r\n\r\nAlmeda was actively involved in the formulation of the bill for the EPIRA Amendments. He was also\r\ntasked with overseeing the privatization process of the various power plants of the National Power\r\nCorporation (NPC).###', '1740381209_media-release-01-01-2048x760.png', '2022-11-22 00:00:00'),
(33, 'BILECO conducts drug test to 50 random employees', 'LOOK: BILECO in coordination with the HQA BIOLAB diagnostic clinic conducts drug test to 50 random employees from the coop onsite of its main office building today, 21 November 2022.\r\nThis was done in pursuant to National Electrification Administration (NEA) advisory to all electric cooperatives in compliance with the guidelines for the implementation of a drug-free workplace and programs for the private sector set by the Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE).', '1740381962_DSC_9242-2048x1365.png', '2022-11-21 00:00:00'),
(34, '‚ÄúMental Health Matters‚Äù', 'BILECO employees underwent a two-day basic training on Psychological First Aid (PFA) at the Paradizu Resort in Brgy. Talahid, Almeria on November 9 to 10 and 16 to 17, 2022, for the first batch and second batch, respectively.\r\nThe activity was conducted by Mr. Cristobal Dexter V. Mendiola III, a Psychosocial Care Specialist from Ormoc City. With PFA, participants were taught on how to help individuals cope and recover from their mental health issues caused by disaster, crisis or emergency events.\r\nDuring the training, participants went through lecture, group discussions including group dynamic activities and experiential learning, in which their diverse reactions and emotions were stimulated.\r\n‚ÄúWe are sociable outside, but maybe we are also struggling inside, like we think a lot of things especially at work, with your dreams, ambitions and family problem.‚Äù BILECO HRAS Michael M. Gabing said.\r\nMr. Gabing together with the human resource personnel of the coop organized the training for its employees to de-stress and learn to practice self-care thereby preventing mental health issues and promoting good health. This activity is in relation to the celebration of the National Cooperatives Month and National Mental Health Awareness Month celebrated last October 2022.##\r\nRead more articles', '1740382054_DSC_6874-2048x1365.jpg', '2022-11-18 00:00:00'),
(35, 'BILECO, TESDA conducts NC II training for barangay electricians', 'BILECO in coordination with Technical Education and Skills Development Authority-Cabucgayan National School of Arts and Trade (TESDA-CNSAT) conducted an Electrical Installation of CCTV and Fire Detection and Alarm System Training held at the Solidarity Hall, 2nd Floor Main Office Building of BILECO on November 7 to 11, 2022.\r\nAs part of its assistance, BILECO paid for the assessment fee of around 40 electricians who attended and joined the training. Most of them came from the BILECO League of Accredited and Skilled Electricians (BLAZE) with expired NC II, while some are BSIT alumni from BiPSU who majored in electricity and recently graduated last September 2022. The training was led by TESDA instructors, Engr. Henry D. Veraque and Zaldy C. Sanico.\r\nTESDA National Certificate II is one of the requirements to be submitted by electricians to BILECO to become one of the accredited electricians of the coop. The accreditation is made mandatory for all practicing electricians to ensure a safe and effective process in performing house wiring installations and in compliance to the standards set forth in the Philippine Electrical Code.', '1740382120_DSC_8097-1-2048x1365.jpg', '2022-11-11 00:00:00'),
(36, 'BILECO undergoes NEA training on CAPEX filing procedures', 'BILECO personnel successfully attended a two-day Capital Expenditures (CAPEX) filing procedure training conducted by the National Electrification Administration (NEA) held on November 3 and 4, 2022 at Marvin‚Äôs Seaside Inn in Brgy. Atipolo, Naval.\r\nThis training was made possible through NEA-Electric Cooperative Training Institute (NETI) headed by Officer-In-Charge Rina R. Dolina who accompanied Engr. Exequiel T. Evale, Jr., the resource speaker of the said training. The participants of the event were the key personnel in the distribution system planning of the coop particularly the CorPlan team together with selected personnel from the technical services department, finance services department, internal audit department and from the office of the general manager.\r\nThe objective of the said training is to equip EC personnel with the necessary knowledge in preparing data and documentary requirements for CAPEX filing with the Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) which primarily includes planning on maintaining power safety, capacity, power quality, reliability, and system loss of its power distribution system; and to be able to comply with regulatory requirements to the commission.', '1740382198_313429097_2383500745149147_4173880728091937502_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(37, 'Emergency Meeting for Typhoon Paeng', 'BILECO General Manager Gerardo Oledan and TSD Manager Carlitus Casinillo spearheaded the emergency meeting for Typhoon Paeng preparation with the Technical team.\r\nGM Oledan reiterated to always monitor radio and phone calls for complaints and requests such as no power or emergency cases related to power service. While, TSD Manager Casinillo reminded the team to be patient during duty and that safety should come first during restoration of power.\r\nRead more articles', '1740382673_313095390_2375198332646055_5263668684006504154_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(38, 'Energy Summit 2022', 'The BILECO League of Accredited and Skilled Electricians (BLAZE) and Barangay Power Association (BAPA) attended the Energy Summit 2022 conducted by BILECO held at its main office on October 14 and 21, 2022, respectively.\r\nThe gathering was initiated by the coop as part of its IEC on the increasing power rates being experienced by electric cooperatives in Region 8. They particularly discussed the reasons behind the increases which come from high generation costs. The bill components was also explained. The technical department, on the other hand, mentioned future projects in 2023 to address power reliability in the province.\r\nBLAZE is composed of accredited electricians coming from the seven districts under BILECO‚Äôs franchise, while BAPA is an allied organization which is the implementing arm of the Meter Reading Billing & Collection Section in selected areas within the coop franchise area.\r\nBoth officers of BLAZE and BAPA took their oath during the event.', '1740382906_312607631_2370721993093689_6380758818928244818_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `content`, `image`, `date`) VALUES
(39, '33rd National Statistics Month', 'BILECO participates in the opening ceremony of the 33rd National Statistics Month with the theme ‚ÄúBoosting the Country‚Äôs Recovery with Informed Decisions, Better Policies‚Äù today at BIPSU Student Center.\r\nThe said activity was also participated by different private & government agencies who discussed a series of presentations. Likewise, GM Gerardo Oledan talked about the issues and concerns regarding the coop‚Äôs power rates.', '1740382991_311084747_2356088657890356_5168658599861141445_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(40, 'BILECO Warriors of Light Champion in Inter-Agency Basketball Tournament', 'Congratulations to the BILECO Warriors of Light for being the Champion in the recently concluded Inter-agency Basketball Tournament of LGU Naval as part of the Town‚Äôs fiesta celebration.\r\nAlso, to the BILECO Electrifiers as they grooved on the dance floor during the cultural and employees‚Äô night presentation held at the BiPSU Gym with a theme ‚ÄúSongs and Dances of the Decades‚Äù.', '1740383058_309913627_2348436911988864_6560057849621942828_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(41, '162nd Naval Pueblo Day', 'LOOK: BILECO joins the 162nd Naval Pueblo Day Celebration through a grand parade held earlier this morning around the town.', '1740383128_308632173_2344500742382481_8985865978879256399_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(42, 'Biliran Provincial Local Price Coordinating Council (LPCC) Meeting', 'The Biliran Provincial Local Price Coordinating Council (LPCC) conducted a meeting together with participating provincial government and private agencies held at Dayen‚Äôs Place in Naval today, September 20, which was hosted by the Department of Trade and Industry Biliran Office.\r\nThe activity was presided by LPCC Chairperson and Provincial Governor Gerard Roger M. Espina. Agencies involved in the distribution of basic and prime commodities including basic utility services such BILECO presented their price and supply monitoring reports in which issues and concerns were raised right after.\r\nGM Gerardo N. Oledan, during his presentation, addressed the high power rates being experienced by electric cooperatives in Region 8 including BILECO, while FSD Manager Ma. Liezyl Q. Garcia discussed the power rate components and the contributory factors resulting to increased power rates.\r\nThe LPC Council is set to have their next meeting on the last week of November 2022 after they have discussed the possible actions that will address the issues and concerns raised during the meeting today', '1740383189_305586246_2339091746256714_3103182826300369759_n.jpg', '2022-11-08 00:00:00'),
(43, 'BILECO holds its 34th Annual General Membership Assembly', 'BILECO held its 34th Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA) on August 27, 2022, with the theme, ‚ÄúLeaving No One Behind: Achieving Social Equitability Through Rural Electrification and Empowerment of Biliran Communities.‚Äù The coop aired the event through Facebook Live on its official FB page in which the members were advise to register in advance using the BILECOnek mobile app and were encouraged to watch the event.\r\nThe Provincial Governor of Biliran, Hon. Gerard Roger M. Espina, was cordially invited as guest speaker of the event but he was represented by Vice-Governor Brigido C. Caneja III due to conflicting schedules. The latter headed the oathtaking of the newly-elected board of directors of BILECO from the seven districts of Biliran during the program.\r\nGeneral Manager Gerardo N. Oledan, in his message, delivered the good news to all its member-consumer-owners on the signing of Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) between the Biliran Geothermal Incorporated (BGI) and BILECO. He mentioned that BGI has a 2.5-megawatt capacity and when it starts to operate will help improve the coop‚Äôs electric distribution service within its franchise area. He added that BILECO has a plan to construct its own generation facility and is expected to be realized by 2026 depending on the coop‚Äôs projected demand.\r\nDuring the preliminaries, FSD Manager Maria Leizyl Q. Garcia discussed and explained the cause of power rate hike which is of great concern to the member-consumer-owners (MCOs) recently. TSD Manager Carlitus Casinillo, likewise followed the said discussion stating the various causes of service power interruptions in the franchise area and reports on power reliability and power quality.\r\nThe AGMA is a yearly event where MCOs gather to discuss the coop‚Äôs report as well as issues affecting the electric distribution utility and the member-consumer-owners.', '1740383287_301839570_2320987071400515_3522951745243591859_n.jpg', '2022-08-29 00:00:00'),
(44, 'National Electrification Awareness Month 2022', 'LOOK: BILECO participated in the 2022 NEA-ECs simultaneous line clearing and tree planting held on August 26.\r\nThe coop‚Äôs linemen conducted line clearing of its distribution lines from Brgy. Caraycaray to Brgy. Larrazabal, Naval. While, a total of 300 assorted seedlings were successfully planted by coop employees in coordination with the Provincial Environment and Natural Resources Office (PENRO) Biliran at Sitio Magtaran-an, Brgy. Talustusan, Naval.\r\nThe said activities are in line with the National Electrification Administration‚Äôs celebration of its 53rd Anniversary and 13th National Electrification Awareness Month (NEAM).', '1740383351_DSC_1268-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-26 00:00:00'),
(45, 'BILECO supports Oplan Balik Eskwela S.Y. 2022-2023', 'Naval Night High School‚Äôs joint Oplan Balik Eskwela for the school year 2022 to 2023 activity kicked-off on August 15, in which BILECO showed support by signing the pledge of commitment thru the Coop‚Äôs Executive Assistant Ms. Ann-Marie Meracap on behalf of GM Gerardo Oledan who was unable to attend the event due to conflict of schedule.\r\nMs. Meracap delivered words of commitment to the school, while BILECO linemen were also present to conduct electrical inspection inside the school premises to ensure safe and reliable supply of power.', '1740383413_DSC_0478-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-16 00:00:00'),
(46, 'BILECO participated in the One-Stop Shop and Job Fair conducted by BiPSU', 'LOOK: BILECO graced and actively participated in the One-Stop Shop and Job Fair held on August 11, 2022, at the Biliran Province State University. True to its theme that no one should be left behind, the event showcased international and local employers providing various job opportunities for employment among job seekers. It also provided convenient and direct services from different national and local agencies.\r\n\r\nThe said activity was organized by BiPSU‚Äôs External Affairs Office and Public Employment Service Office (PESO).', '1740383463_DSC_0233-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-12 00:00:00'),
(47, 'BILECO Linemen Participated in the Line Workers‚Äô Appreciation Day', 'BILECO lineworkers participated in the celebration of Line Workers Appreciation Day together with the National Electrification Administration (NEA) and 120 electric cooperatives in the country.\r\nThe event was set-up and streamed via Facebook live on August 23, 2022. It was part of the NEA‚Äôs 53rd Anniversary and 13th National Electrification Awareness Month (NEAM) with the theme ‚ÄúNEA at ECs: Magkatuwang sa Pag-unlad at Pagkakaisa Tungo sa Bagong Pag-asa‚Äù.\r\nOn the same day, TSD Manager Carlitus Caesar Casinillo along with the TSD engineers, had a lecture session to the lineworkers of the coop about renewable energy, electrical safety and they were reminded on the proper use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).', '1740383574_DSC_1076-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-08 00:00:00'),
(48, 'BILECO Employees attend the Good Customer Service and Cooperative Branding Seminar', 'BILECO employees coming from the Institutional Services Department (ISD), Office of the General Manager (OGM), and Internal Audit Department (IAD) attended the good customer service and coop branding seminar today, August 18. It can be recalled that the coop‚Äôs linemen also underwent the same seminar last August 5 and 8 with the same speaker, the Acting Cooperative Communications & Social Marketing Office Head, Ms. Ann-Marie Meracap.\r\n\r\nThis activity was done through GM Gerardo Oledan‚Äôs directive with the purpose to upgrade and update the skills of its employees especially on how to properly communicate with the MCOs of the coop.', '1740383645_DSC_9905-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-08 00:00:00'),
(49, 'BILECO linemen undergo good customer service, coop branding seminar', 'BILECO employees belonging to the Technical Services Department mostly consisting of line workers underwent a seminar on good customer service and cooperative branding in two batches that was held at the coop‚Äôs main office building on August 5 & 8, for the first batch and second batch, respectively. The participants were scheduled on separate dates to ensure that there will be a crew on duty available to respond on complaints and requests while the other batch is attending the seminar.\r\n\r\nAccording to GM Gerardo Oledan, the purpose of this seminar is to upgrade and update the skills of its employees especially on how to properly deal with the MCOs of the coop. The speaker of the event is the Acting Cooperative Communications & Social Marketing Office Head, Ms. Ann-Marie Meracap, where she discussed The Eight Core Principles of Good Customer Service and Cooperative Branding to the attendees.\r\n\r\nThe management thru the leadership of GM Oledan is set to conduct the same seminar on customer service in the coming days for all its employees of the other three departments: ISD, OGM/IAD and FSD.', '1740383703_DSC_0161-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-07 00:00:00'),
(50, 'Lineman from BILECO awardee of PHILRECA‚Äôs 2022 Gawad Parangal Para sa Natatanging Linemen', 'Congratulations to Juanito Garcia Jr.!\r\n\r\nMr. Juanito Garcia Jr. of BILECO is one of the awardees from Region 8 recognized and awarded by the Philippine Rural Electrification Cooperatives Association, Inc. (PHILRECA) during the 2022 Gawad Parangal Para sa Natatanging Linemen virtual event held today, August 1.\r\n\r\nThe event was initiated by PHILRECA in celebration of the Linemen Appreciation Day celebrated by all electric cooperatives in the country on every first Monday of August of every year.\r\n\r\nMr. Garcia received a token, certificate and check worth 3,000 pesos from PHILRECA for the said recognition. Again, congratulations from your BILECO Family!', '1740383766_DSC_8779-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-01 00:00:00'),
(51, 'BILECO celebrates 2022 linemen appreciation day', 'BILECO celebrated Linemen Appreciation Day for all its warriors of light held at the main office in Brgy. Caraycaray, Naval on August 1, 2022, Monday.\r\nIn his message during the program, GM Gerardo Oledan reiterated that for three consecutive years, the Coop has consistently acheived the AAA categorization as an electric distribution utility. With that, he thanked all the linemen on their efforts and dedication in keeping the lights on and encouraged them to continue exemplifying these qualities in their day-to-day tasks and duties.\r\nLinemen appreciation day is an annual celebration by the 121 electric cooperatives all over the country to acknowledge and give importance to a lineman‚Äôs job and recognize their contribution to rural electrification.', '1740383889_DSC_8715-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-08-01 00:00:00'),
(52, 'New BOD of Naval proclaimed', 'A new board of director was elected and duly proclaimed by the District Election Committee (DECOM) for Naval District during the conduct of regular district election last July 30, 2022, Saturday, at the Naval Central School, P.I. Garcia, Naval with six designated precinct areas. One of these precincts was placed at the Brgy. Mabini covered court in Higatangan Island with a Precinct Election Committee (PECOM) assigned.\r\nIn the combined result, Mrs. Milagros O. Caneja garnered a total vote of 428 against 117 votes obtained by Mr. Ronald Napala. After canvassing, the DECOM led by Chairperson Mrs. Alma Atibula proclaimed BOD-elect Mrs. Caneja as the winning candidate. She will officially swear the oath of office together with the other BOD-elect from the six Districts of Biliran on August 27, 2022 during the 34th Annual General Membership Assembly (AGMA).', '1740383966_DSC_8702-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-07-30 00:00:00'),
(53, 'Incumbent director in Kawayan once again elected as BOD', 'Incumbent Director Mr. Wilberto Caridad once again elected as Board of Director in Kawayan District after BILECO conducted its regular district election on July 23, Saturday at the Kawayan Central School. Caridad garnering a total vote of 108 was a lone candidate from his town.', '1740384076_DSC_8227-2048x1367.jpg', '2022-07-23 00:00:00'),
(54, 'President BBM vetoes house bill expanding Davao Light and Power‚Äôs franchise; upholds vital role of electric cooperatives in total electrification and national development', 'In a letter addressed to the Senate and House of Representatives yesterday, President Ferdinand R. Marcos, Jr. sent his veto message of House Bill 10554 or An Act Expanding the Franchise Area of Davao Light and Power Company, Inc.\r\nPresident Marcos echoed the declared national policy in PD 269 on total electrification of the Philippines which remains ‚Äúvital to the welfare of our people and the sound development of the Nation.‚Äù\r\n\r\n‚ÄúI remain committed to the pursuit and attainment of this objective in a vigorous and systematic manner, with utmost respect for the concomitant rights of the public service entities engaged in supplying electric service,‚Äù the President said in his communication to the legislative bodies.\r\n\r\nThough he recognized the legislative measure‚Äôs intent to further improve the public‚Äôs access to electricity, President Marcos said that he is ‚Äúconstrained to veto the bill due to the susceptibility of the proposed expansion of the franchise area of Davao Light and Power Company, Inc. to legal and/or constitutional challenge due to the apparent overlap and possible infringement into the subsisting franchise, permits, and contracts previously granted to North Davao Electric Cooperative Inc.‚Äù\r\n\r\nPresident Marcos also acknowledged the fact that NORDECO‚Äôs franchise will only end in 2033. According to the President, House Bill 10554, which aims to kill the EC‚Äôs franchise, ‚Äúruns counter to the provisions of Section 27 of Republic Act No. 9136 or the EPIRA mandating that all existing franchises shall be allowed in its full term.‚Äù\r\n\r\n‚ÄúLikewise, the resulting repeal of North Davao Electric Cooperative Inc.‚Äôs franchise over the expanded franchise area will violate the non-impairment clause as provided in Section 10, Article III of the 1987 Constitution,‚Äù the President added.\r\n\r\nThe President also emphasized that House Bill 10554 ‚Äúis a prohibited collateral attach on North Davao Electric Cooperative Inc. franchise‚Äù and such bill ‚Äúis contrary to a jurisprudentially settled doctrine that a franchise cannot be subjected to a ‚Äòcollateral attack‚Äô‚Äù.\r\n\r\nDuring public hearings in the House of Representatives and the Senate, PHILRECA, the association of electric cooperatives operating nationwide, has unequivocally opposed House Bill 10554 due to similar reasons.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúNORDECO was granted a franchise by virtue of Certificates No. 017 and 103 issued by the National Electrification Administration for a period of fifty (50) years from 1978 and 1983, respectively, which means the existing franchise of NORDECO, will only expire in 2033,‚Äù explained Atty. Janeene Depay-Colingan, PHILRECA‚Äôs Executive Director in its position paper submitted to the Office of the President.\r\n\r\n‚ÄúIn addition to the protection categorically guaranteed by RA 9136 or the EPIRA and non-impairment clause of the Constitution, R.A 6038 is very clear that no franchise for service shall be granted to any other person within any area or portion for which a cooperative holds a franchise,‚Äù PHILRECA stated in its letter to the President.\r\n\r\nPHILRECA‚Äôs position paper further explained that ‚Äúfor more than 50 years, we have relied on electric cooperatives as they risk their lives to energize the countryside, especially the far-flung areas which big, for-profit corporations neglected because there is no potential of profit. The electric cooperatives reiterate their commitment in being staunch partners of the government in total electrification and nation building of the country as they have done in the last 5 decades of rural electrification.‚Äù\r\n\r\nThey concluded that ‚Äúthe electric cooperatives do not intent to profit or be rewarded on their sacrifices; but allowing them to continue being the government‚Äôs partner for electrification is not only going to be beneficial to the member-consumer-owners, but more importantly, this is the right thing to do.‚Äù\r\n\r\n‚ÄúWe thank the President for acting positively on the Movement‚Äôs plight against takeover of ECs by private for-profit corporation and oligarchs like Davao Light and Power Company,‚Äù said Colingan on the President‚Äôs veto of House Bill 10554.\r\n\r\nShe added that ‚Äúelectric cooperatives should remain to be owned and operated by the people, not by the oligarchs, not by the few elites,‚Äù and that the organization and all its member-electric cooperatives appreciate the President‚Äôs recognition of the vital role of the sector in national development. ###', '1740442716_unnamed-6.jpg', '2022-07-23 00:00:00');

